where the components \delta _{i,j} are referred to as the Kronecker Delta.

Let m, n be positive integers. We define an m-by-n Matrix \mathbf {A} to be a rectangular array of mn real [or complex] numbers arranged in m horizontal Rows and n vertical Columns, written:
\mathbf {A} = \left (\begin {array}{cccccc}   a_{11} & a_{12} & … & a_{1j} & … & a_{1n} \\ a_{21} & a_{22} & … & a_{2j} & … & a_{2n}  \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ a_{i1} & a_{i2} & … & a_{ij} & … & a_{in} \\ \vdots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ a_{m1} & a_{m2} & …   & a_{mj} & …  & a_{mn}  \end {array}\right ) \begin {array}{c}   \\   \gets  i^{\text {th}}\hbox {\ row} \end {array}
We have highlighted the i^{\text {th}} row, and the j^{\text {th}} column.

One method to find a solution, which has been taught to high school students for decades, is to take the first equation and use it to rewrite one variable in terms of the remaining. For example, in:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}     0      & + & 2x_{2} & + & 3x_{3} & = & 5\\     2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\     x_{1}  & + & x_{2}  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.   \end {array}
We would use the first equation to substitute x_{2}=(5 - 3x_{3})/2 in the remaining equations, and discard the first equation, giving us:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}     2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\     x_{1}  & + & \displaystyle \left (\frac {5 - 3x_{3}}{2}\right )  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.   \end {array}
We do this again, to use the first equation to write x_{1} = (-1-3x_{3})/2, and plug this into the last equation, which gives us a value for x_{3}.

One class of systems of linear equations occurs naturally in Neo-Ricardian economics. Consider a hypothetical economy consisting of two industry sectors, wheat and iron, whose production processes are described by the system of equations (where the left of the arrow refers to the inputs at the start of the production period, and the quantities to the right of the arrows are produced at the end of the period, and then an annual market takes place where iron is traded for wheat):
\begin {array}{rcl} \hbox {inputs} & \to  & \hbox {outputs}\\ 280~\hbox {qr. wheat} + 12~\hbox {t. iron} & \to  & 400~\hbox {qr. wheat}\\ 120~\hbox {qr. wheat} + 8~\hbox {t. iron}  & \to  &  20~\hbox {t. iron}. \end {array}
The question we want to know: what is the exchange rate between quarters of wheat and tons of iron?

We can create a system of equations by introducing two unknowns p_{w} for the price of 1 quarter of wheat, and p_{i} for the price of 1 ton of iron. We assume society is in a "self reproducing state", in the sense that the wheat sector exchanges enough wheat-for-iron to continue producing wheat (and the iron sector exchanges enough iron-for-wheat to continue producing iron):
\begin {array}{rcl}     280p_{w} + 12p_{i} &=& 400p_{w}\\     120p_{w} + 8p_{i} &=& 20p_{i}. \end {array}
We can rewrite the first equation (by subtracting both sides by 280p_{w}):
\begin {array}{rcl}     12p_{i} &=& 120p_{w}\\     120p_{w} + 8p_{i} &=& 20p_{i}. \end {array}
Then we rewrite the second equation (by subtracting both sides by 8p_{i}):
\begin {array}{rcl}     12p_{i} &=& 120p_{w}\\     120p_{w} &=& 12p_{i}. \end {array}
These are redundant equations! We end up with a class of solutions, described by
\boxed {10p_{w} = p_{i},}
that is to say, the price of 1 ton iron is equal to the price of 10 quarters of wheat.

More generally, a System of m Linear Equations in n Unknowns  x_{1}, …, x_{n} (where the subscripts are Indices to append to one symbol x a number or "dummy variable" [a variable ranging over the index values], giving us any number of variables for the price of one symbol) looks like:
\begin {array}{rcl} a_{1,1}x_{1} + a_{1,2}x_{2} + … + a_{1,n}x_{n} &=& b_{1}\\ a_{2,1}x_{1} + a_{2,2}x_{2} + … + a_{2,n}x_{n} &=& b_{2}\\ \vdots \quad  \qquad \vdots \quad \qquad \ddots \quad \qquad \vdots \quad  & \vdots  & \vdots \\ a_{m,1}x_{1} + a_{m,2}x_{2} + … + a_{m,n}x_{n} &=& b_{m} \end {array}
where b_{1}, …, b_{m} are m real constants, and we have a_{1,1}, a_{1,2}, …, a_{m,n} be mn real constants called the Coefficients.

One method to find a solution, which has been taught to high school students for decades, is to take the first equation and use it to rewrite one variable in terms of the remaining. For example, in:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}     0      & + & 2x_{2} & + & 3x_{3} & = & 5\\     2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\     x_{1}  & + & x_{2}  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.   \end {array}
We would use the first equation to substitute x_{2}=(5 - 3x_{3})/2 in the remaining equations, and discard the first equation, giving us:
\begin {array}{rcrcrcl}     2x_{1} & + & 0      & + & 3x_{3} &=& -1\\     x_{1}  & + & \displaystyle \left (\frac {5 - 3x_{3}}{2}\right )  & + & x_{3} &=& 1.   \end {array}
We do this again, to use the first equation to write x_{1} = (-1-3x_{3})/2, and plug this into the last equation, which gives us a value for x_{3}.

More generally, a System of m Linear Equations in n Unknowns  x_{1}, …, x_{n} (where the subscripts are Indices to append to one symbol x a number or "dummy variable" [a variable ranging over the index values], giving us any number of variables for the price of one symbol) looks like:
\begin {array}{rcl} a_{1,1}x_{1} + a_{1,2}x_{2} + … + a_{1,n}x_{n} &=& b_{1}\\ a_{2,1}x_{1} + a_{2,2}x_{2} + … + a_{2,n}x_{n} &=& b_{2}\\ \vdots \quad  \qquad \vdots \quad \qquad \ddots \quad \qquad \vdots \quad  & \vdots  & \vdots \\ a_{m,1}x_{1} + a_{m,2}x_{2} + … + a_{m,n}x_{n} &=& b_{m} \end {array}
where b_{1}, …, b_{m} are m real constants, and we have a_{1,1}, a_{1,2}, …, a_{m,n} be mn real constants called the Coefficients.

The function f\colon \mathbb {R}^{n}\to \mathbb {R} defined by
f(x_{1},…,x_{n})=\left (\sum ^{n}_{i=1}x_{i}^{2}\right )^{1/2}
is a norm known as the "Euclidean norm".
